         I. I  have  a  friend  in Russia that I would like to send my
            translated files to via  electronic  mail.  My  electronic
            mail  system  only accepts ASCII and this document will be
            used to create a contract so I can  not  use  the  Tel-Lex
            mode. How can I sent my translated file?

              We have  included  three files on the distribution disk.
              They are compiled into  one  file  for  extraction.  The
              extraction file is ATGGTA.EXE. This program contains the
              following programs or files:

              LTGTA.EXE ﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄ Graphics (Cyrillics) to ASCII
              LTATG.EXE ﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄ ASCII to Graphics
              README.DOC ﾄﾄﾄﾄ Instructions on how to use the programs

              If you were going to send a Russian file via  Electronic
              mail and your file name was RUSSIAN.TXT you would type:

              LTGTA RUSSIAN.TXT RUSSIAN.ASC
                ｳ        ｳ           ﾀﾄ output file
                ｳ        ﾀﾄ input file
                ﾀﾄ graphics to ascii

              Once received in Russia the following would be  used  to
              convert the file back:

              LTATG RUSSIAN.ASC RUSSIAN.TXT
                ｳ        ｳ           ﾀﾄ output file
                ｳ        ﾀﾄ input file
                ﾀﾄ ascii to graphics

              These programs are free for distribution by any licensed
              user of LTGOLD,  LTPRO, and LTDICS and for use only with
              the above mentioned programs. No fee or compensation can
              be  received  for  their distribution by any party other
              than  the  author  or  their  authorized   dealers   and
              distributors.


                                    - 13 -
                                  LTGOLD Q&A

         J.  When  would I use the Tel-Lex (R) mode and is it readable
             for most Russians?

              The Tel-Lex mode  was  developed  to  overcome  a  major
              international   Telex   problem   (and   most   recently
              Electronic Mail systems).  Telex systems only allow  the
              normal  ASCII characters.  Cyrillics are not usable even
              in Russia.  Most Russian  companies  are  used  to  this
              format   and  can  fully  understand  the  text.  It  is
              important to remember that most Russians  learned  basic
              English  in  school.  The  pronunciation  of the letters
              created by this mode should not  create  a  problem  for
              your recipient.

              An additional use for the Tel-Lex mode is to help in the
              pronunciation of Russian words.  Most of those  starting
              to learn Russian like this feature to assist in learning
              the proper pronunciation of Russian words.  The  student
              should learn  to read and pronounce Cyrillics as soon as
              possible, this feature may help in this process.

         K.  Is there  a  way  to  see  how  many  words  the  program
             translated while I am in the program?

              Yes, You  are  able to turn "Statistics" on and off from
              the "Options" menu.  You can review  statistics  anytime
              from the "File" menu.

         L.  I  would  like  to  charge  $.25  a word for every word I
             translate. Can the program calculate this for me?

              Yes, the statistics screen gives  you  this  information
              and  the rate can be modified from the "File" menu.  The
              currency does not matter as you  only  set  the  numeric
              value.

         M.  I notice the program transliterates my state, California.
             I would  like  to leave  it  in  an  English  format  for
             addressing envelopes. How do I accomplish this?

              Most countries,  states,  cities, and personal names are
              transliterated by the program. If you would like to keep
              the English form, from the "Options" menu select "Format
              Output File.."  and turn off Transliteration (remove the
              [X] by pressing return over the selection).

         N.  Can  I  change  the different options at any point of the
             translation process?

              Yes, there are two ways to do this. The first is to turn
              on the "Edit Each Sentence" mode from the "Options" menu
              and  hit  Esc  (Escape)  when  you  want  to  change the
              options.  The second way is to hit Esc when the  program
              is  processing  a  document and the program will suspend
              the translation and allow you to change the options.




